Apple-1 Emulator Documentation
================================

Portable, terminal-based Apple-1 emulator written in C. Core emulation code talks
only to port.h; platform I/O lives in port_*.c shims (POSIX, MS-DOS, Windows,
and others).

Quick start
-----------

    make                  # build ./apple1
    make check            # run unit tests
    ./apple1 -r wozmon.bin

Headless CPU test (no terminal UI):

    ./apple1 -H -F wozmon.bin

Documentation index
-------------------

    building.md       Makefile targets, amalgamation, cross-compilation (MS-DOS), tests
    configuration.md  Compile-time limits, APPLE1_OMIT_* flags, port layer, malloc modes
    usage.md          Command-line options, config files, keyboard shortcuts, examples
    debugger.md       Interactive debugger commands
    hardware.md       Memory map, PIA, expansion cards, timing

Project layout (essentials)
---------------------------

    main.c              CLI entry point
    cpu.c bus.c         6502 CPU and system bus
    term_ansi.c         Terminal UI (ANSI escapes — POSIX/macOS/Linux)
    term_dos.c          Terminal UI (conio — MS-DOS/DJGPP)
    port.h              Portability interface (types + shims)
    port_string.c       Freestanding string/format helpers (all builds)
    port_posix.c        POSIX platform implementation (default on Unix)
    port_msdos.c        MS-DOS platform implementation
    apple1limit.h       Compile-time limits and defaults
    tools/amalgamate.py Single-file apple1.c generator

What this emulator is (and is not)
------------------------------------

Is: a cycle-oriented Apple-1 model with Woz Monitor, optional ACI cassette
card, optional Krusader ROM, CLI debugger, and a 40×24 terminal display.

Is not: the old SDL3 GUI build (removed). All interaction is via the terminal
and command line.
